<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="416" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1052,1599]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1052,1078]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1873" box="[280,414,1052,1078]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Glyptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[280,414,1052,1078]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Glyptobasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[559,653,1052,1078]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Acheron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[559,653,1052,1078]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Acheron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having the distinct lateral spines on the basal flagellomeres in male and similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Navas" authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1923" box="[315,488,1087,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Nousera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[315,410,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Nousera</emphasis>
Navás
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a distinct triangular projection on the anal area of forewing. The genus can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lefebvre" authorityYear="1842" box="[529,623,1121,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Acheron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[529,623,1121,1147]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Acheron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of the distinct triangular projection on the anal area of forewing and from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Navas" authorityYear="1923" box="[368,463,1157,1182]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Nousera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[368,463,1157,1182]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Nousera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of distinct lateral spines on the basal antennal segments in male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,1052,1599]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,262,1191,1217]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Note.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="McLachlan" authorityYear="1873" box="[272,406,1191,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Glyptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[272,406,1191,1217]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Glyptobasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is represented by eight species which are mostly restricted to South Asia (5 species) and Southeast Asia (3 spp.). The greatest diversity of this genus occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[945,1003,1225,1251]" name="India" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">India</collectingCountry>
(5 spp.) and 
<collectingCountry box="[1154,1263,1226,1252]" name="Myanmar" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
(3 spp.). However, the discovery of members of this genus, i.e., 
<taxonomicName authority="(Westwood, 1847)" baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[711,1167,1260,1286]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Glyptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentifera">
<emphasis box="[711,953,1260,1286]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Glyptobasis dentifera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Westwood, J. O." box="[967,1160,1260,1286]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" refId="ref28983" refString="Westwood, J. O. (1847) The Cabinet of Oriental Entomology; being a selection of the rarer and more beautiful species of insects, natives of India and the adjacent islands. The greater portion of which are now, for the first time, described and figured. Smith, London, 88 pp. [BotN ref  6259] https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 34273" type="book" year="1847">Westwood, 1847</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, from 
<collectingCountry box="[1240,1335,1260,1286]" name="Pakistan" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
suggests that the fauna of eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[426,521,1295,1321]" name="Pakistan" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
is of Oriental affinity. The specimen we examined agrees with the photographs of 
<typeStatus box="[151,249,1330,1356]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[285,419,1329,1356]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Glyptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentifera">
<emphasis box="[285,419,1329,1356]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">G. dentifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Tauber, C. A. &amp; Simmons, Z. &amp; Tauber, A. J." box="[453,672,1329,1355]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" pagination="1 - 126" refId="ref28652" refString="Tauber, C. A., Simmons, Z. &amp; Tauber, A. J. (2019) Type specimens of Neuropterida in the Hope Entomological Collection, Oxford University Museum of Natural History. ZooKeys, 823, 1 - 126. [BotN ref  18513] https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 823.30231" type="journal article" year="2019">
Tauber 
<emphasis box="[536,591,1329,1355]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
in regard to general morphology, except for slight color variations in the wing membrane, which are slightly brownish along the costal region in forewing and also on the apical region of hind wing in the photographs of 
<typeStatus box="[551,653,1399,1425]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">syntypes</typeStatus>
. In our specimen the wings are completely hyaline. For now, we treat our specimen as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[336,577,1433,1459]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Glyptobasis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dentifera">
<emphasis box="[336,577,1433,1459]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Glyptobasis dentifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, based on comparison with photographs provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tauber, C. A. &amp; Simmons, Z. &amp; Tauber, A. J." box="[1170,1390,1433,1459]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" pagination="1 - 126" refId="ref28652" refString="Tauber, C. A., Simmons, Z. &amp; Tauber, A. J. (2019) Type specimens of Neuropterida in the Hope Entomological Collection, Oxford University Museum of Natural History. ZooKeys, 823, 1 - 126. [BotN ref  18513] https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 823.30231" type="journal article" year="2019">
Tauber 
<emphasis box="[1254,1309,1433,1459]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">et al.</emphasis>
(2019)
</bibRefCitation>
and hope that future discovery of a male from 
<collectingCountry box="[627,722,1468,1494]" name="Pakistan" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
will yield information on the correct identification. The similar variability of color patterns on wing membrane has also been noticed in some other split-eyed owlfly species, such as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker, 1853)" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[181,533,1537,1564]" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Acheron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longus">
<emphasis box="[181,357,1537,1563]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Acheron longus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Walker, F." box="[371,524,1537,1564]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" refId="ref28820" refString="Walker, F. (1853) Catalogue of the specimens of neuropterous insects in the collection of the British Museum. Part II (Sialidae- Nemopterides). Newman, London, 284 pp. [pp. 193 - 476, BotN ref  6194]" type="book" year="1853">Walker, 1853</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tauber, C. A. &amp; Simmons, Z. &amp; Tauber, A. J." box="[579,794,1537,1563]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" pagination="1 - 126" refId="ref28652" refString="Tauber, C. A., Simmons, Z. &amp; Tauber, A. J. (2019) Type specimens of Neuropterida in the Hope Entomological Collection, Oxford University Museum of Natural History. ZooKeys, 823, 1 - 126. [BotN ref  18513] https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 823.30231" type="journal article" year="2019">
Tauber 
<emphasis box="[663,719,1537,1563]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">et al.</emphasis>
(2019
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 15A–C) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Abraham, L." box="[998,1200,1537,1566]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" pagination="63 - 77" refId="ref25419" refString="Abraham, L. (2008 b) Ascalaphid studies VII. On the ascalaphid fauna of Taiwan (Neuroptera: Ascalaphidae). Natura Somogyiensis, 12, 63 - 77. [BotN ref  14316]" type="journal article" year="2008">Ábrahám (2008b)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Westwood, 1847)" baseAuthorityName="Westwood" baseAuthorityYear="1847" class="Insecta" family="Ascalaphidae" genus="Ogcogaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tessellata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Ogcogaster tessellata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Westwood, J. O." box="[240,431,1572,1598]" pageId="15" pageNumber="416" refId="ref28983" refString="Westwood, J. O. (1847) The Cabinet of Oriental Entomology; being a selection of the rarer and more beautiful species of insects, natives of India and the adjacent islands. The greater portion of which are now, for the first time, described and figured. Smith, London, 88 pp. [BotN ref  6259] https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 34273" type="book" year="1847">Westwood, 1847</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[454,594,1572,1598]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[418,1162,192,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-19@24.[407,1181,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 14. Ogcogaster tessellata (Westwood). Male. A–C. Dorsal habitus. Scale bar: 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4766595" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4766595/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">Figs 14A–C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[605,689,1572,1599]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1084,1108]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,201,1056]" captionTargetId="figure-19@25.[151,1436,181,1060]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 15. Ogcogaster tessellata (Westwood). Female. A–D. Dorsal habitus. Scale bar: 5.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4766597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4766597/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="416">15A–D</figureCitation>
) in the present study.
</paragraph>
